for_developers/README.md
     1‚Üí# For developers
     3‚ÜíWhile `mdbook` is mainly used as a command line tool, you can also import the
     4‚Üíunderlying libraries directly and use those to manage a book. It also has a fairly
     5‚Üíflexible plugin mechanism, allowing you to create your own custom tooling and
     6‚Üíconsumers (often referred to as *backends*) if you need to do some analysis of
     7‚Üíthe book or render it in a different format.
     8‚Üí
     9‚ÜíThe *For Developers* chapters are here to show you the more advanced usage of
    10‚Üí`mdbook`.
    11‚Üí
    12‚ÜíThe two main ways a developer can hook into the book's build process is via,
    13‚Üí
    14‚Üí- [Preprocessors](preprocessors.md)
    15‚Üí- [Alternative Backends](backends.md)
    16‚Üí
    17‚Üí## The build process
    19‚ÜíThe process of rendering a book project goes through several steps.
    20‚Üí
    21‚Üí1. Load the book
    22‚Üí    - Parse the `book.toml`, falling back to the default `Config` if it doesn't
    23‚Üí       exist
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
    30‚Üí## Using `mdbook` as a library
    32‚ÜíThe `mdbook` binary is just a wrapper around the underlying mdBook crates,
    33‚Üíexposing their functionality as a command-line program. If you want to
    34‚Üíprogrammatically drive mdBook, you can use the [`mdbook-driver`] crate.
    35‚ÜíThis can be used to add your own functionality or tweak the build process.
    36‚Üí
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
for_developers/backends.md
     1‚Üí# Alternative backends
     3‚ÜíA "backend" is simply a program which `mdbook` will invoke during the book
     4‚Üírendering process. This program is passed a JSON representation of the book and
     5‚Üíconfiguration information via `stdin`. Once the backend receives this
     6‚Üíinformation it is free to do whatever it wants.
     7‚Üí
     8‚ÜíSee [Configuring Renderers](../format/configuration/renderers.md) for more information about using backends.
     9‚Üí
    10‚ÜíThe community has developed several backends.
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
